const listeningTopics = [
  { title: "University Lecture on Marine Biology", category: "Academic", difficulty: "Intermediate",
    transcript: "Good morning, everyone. Today we'll be discussing marine ecosystems and the role of keystone species. A keystone species is one that has a disproportionately large effect on its environment relative to its abundance. The classic example is the sea otter, which preys on sea urchins. Without sea otters, urchin populations explode and devour kelp forests. This phenomenon was first documented by Robert Paine in the 1960s. The concept has since been applied to terrestrial ecosystems as well. Understanding keystone species is crucial for conservation planning." },
  { title: "Radio Discussion on Urban Planning", category: "General", difficulty: "Beginner",
    transcript: "Welcome to City Talk. Today we're discussing the concept of walkable cities. Our guest, Dr. Sarah Chen, has spent twenty years studying urban mobility. Dr. Chen, what makes a city walkable? Well, it comes down to several factors: mixed-use zoning that puts homes near shops and offices, safe pedestrian infrastructure, and pleasant streetscapes with trees and lighting. Cities like Copenhagen and Amsterdam have shown that reducing car dependency improves quality of life, reduces pollution, and even boosts local economies." },
  { title: "Business Presentation on Market Trends", category: "Business", difficulty: "Advanced",
    transcript: "Thank you for joining this quarterly review. I'd like to highlight three key market trends we've identified. First, consumer preferences are shifting toward sustainable products, with 65% of respondents willing to pay more for eco-friendly options. Second, the subscription economy continues to grow at 18% annually. Third, personalization driven by artificial intelligence is becoming the standard expectation. Companies that fail to adapt to these trends risk losing market share. Let me walk you through our strategic response to each of these developments." },
  { title: "Museum Audio Guide: Ancient Egypt", category: "Cultural", difficulty: "Beginner",
    transcript: "Welcome to the Ancient Egypt gallery. The artifact before you is a canopic jar dating from the 18th Dynasty, approximately 1400 BCE. These jars were used during mummification to store and preserve the internal organs of the deceased. Four jars were typically used, each protected by a different deity. The liver was guarded by Imsety, the lungs by Hapi, the stomach by Duamutef, and the intestines by Qebehsenuef. This particular jar features an elaborately carved limestone lid and hieroglyphic inscriptions identifying its owner." },
  { title: "Podcast on Artificial Intelligence Ethics", category: "Technology", difficulty: "Advanced",
    transcript: "The question isn't whether AI will transform society, but how we ensure it does so fairly. Algorithmic bias has already been documented in criminal justice, hiring, and lending systems. When training data reflects historical inequalities, AI systems perpetuate and sometimes amplify these biases. Transparency in algorithm design and diverse development teams are essential safeguards. The European Union's AI Act represents the first comprehensive attempt to regulate artificial intelligence. However, balancing innovation with protection remains a significant challenge for policymakers worldwide." },
  { title: "Travel Documentary: Japanese Culture", category: "Cultural", difficulty: "Intermediate",
    transcript: "Japan's unique cultural traditions reflect centuries of isolation and careful cultivation. The tea ceremony, or chado, embodies the principles of harmony, respect, purity, and tranquility. Each movement is deliberate and meaningful, transforming a simple act of preparing tea into a meditative practice. Similarly, ikebana, the art of flower arrangement, emphasizes asymmetry and space as much as the flowers themselves. These aesthetic principles extend to architecture, garden design, and even cuisine, where presentation is considered as important as taste." },
  { title: "Health Seminar: Nutrition Myths", category: "Health", difficulty: "Beginner",
    transcript: "Let's debunk some common nutrition myths today. First, eating fat doesn't necessarily make you fat. Healthy fats from sources like avocados, nuts, and olive oil are essential for brain function and hormone production. Second, carbohydrates are not inherently bad. Whole grains, fruits, and vegetables provide crucial fiber and nutrients. Third, detox diets are largely unnecessary as your liver and kidneys already perform this function naturally. The key to good nutrition is balance, variety, and moderation rather than following restrictive diet trends." },
  { title: "Academic Debate on Free Trade", category: "Academic", difficulty: "Advanced",
    transcript: "The free trade debate has intensified in recent years with rising protectionist sentiment. Proponents argue that comparative advantage allows countries to specialize in what they produce most efficiently, lowering prices for consumers. Critics counter that free trade agreements have hollowed out manufacturing sectors in developed nations, leading to job losses and wage stagnation. The evidence suggests a nuanced picture where trade liberalization generates net economic gains but distributes them unevenly. Effective policy must therefore combine trade openness with domestic programs that support displaced workers." },
  { title: "Nature Documentary: Arctic Wildlife", category: "Nature", difficulty: "Intermediate",
    transcript: "The Arctic region, despite its harsh conditions, supports a remarkable diversity of life. Polar bears, the apex predators of this ecosystem, rely on sea ice to hunt ringed seals. As climate change reduces ice coverage, polar bears face increasing difficulty finding food. Arctic foxes demonstrate remarkable adaptations, changing their coat color from white in winter to brown in summer. Migratory species like the Arctic tern travel an astonishing 70,000 kilometers annually between the Arctic and Antarctic. The interconnectedness of Arctic species means that changes affecting one species ripple through the entire ecosystem." },
  { title: "Student Conversation: Study Abroad", category: "General", difficulty: "Beginner",
    transcript: "Hey, are you thinking about the study abroad program? Yeah, I'm really interested in the one in Barcelona. My advisor said it's great for language immersion. The application deadline is next month, and you need a minimum GPA of 3.0. The program covers tuition and housing but you need to arrange your own flights. I heard the classes are taught in both English and Spanish. That sounds perfect since I'm minoring in Spanish. Have you talked to anyone who's done it? Yes, my roommate went last year and said it was the best experience of her college life." },
  { title: "Environmental Conference Keynote", category: "Academic", difficulty: "Advanced",
    transcript: "Distinguished colleagues, we stand at a critical juncture in environmental policy. The latest IPCC report indicates we have less than a decade to halve global emissions if we are to limit warming to 1.5 degrees Celsius. The technologies we need largely exist already: renewable energy, electric vehicles, energy-efficient buildings, and sustainable agriculture. What we lack is the political will and economic incentives to deploy them at scale. Carbon pricing mechanisms, whether through carbon taxes or cap-and-trade systems, have proven effective where implemented. However, international cooperation remains insufficient." },
  { title: "Cooking Show: Mediterranean Diet", category: "Health", difficulty: "Beginner",
    transcript: "Today we're exploring the Mediterranean diet, which has been recognized by UNESCO as an intangible cultural heritage. This way of eating emphasizes fruits, vegetables, whole grains, legumes, nuts, and olive oil. Fish and seafood are consumed regularly, while red meat is limited to a few times per month. Studies consistently show that the Mediterranean diet reduces the risk of heart disease, diabetes, and certain cancers. The social aspect is equally important: meals are typically shared with family and friends, eaten slowly, and savored. Let me show you how to prepare a classic Greek salad." },
  { title: "Technology Conference: Cloud Computing", category: "Technology", difficulty: "Intermediate",
    transcript: "Cloud computing has fundamentally changed how businesses operate and scale. The three main service models are Infrastructure as a Service, Platform as a Service, and Software as a Service. Companies no longer need to maintain expensive on-premises servers. Instead, they can access computing resources on demand, paying only for what they use. Security remains a primary concern, with multi-cloud strategies becoming increasingly popular to avoid vendor lock-in. Edge computing is emerging as a complement to cloud services, processing data closer to where it's generated to reduce latency." },
  { title: "History Lecture: Industrial Revolution", category: "Academic", difficulty: "Intermediate",
    transcript: "The Industrial Revolution, which began in Britain in the late 18th century, was perhaps the most significant transformation in human history. The shift from agricultural to industrial economies was driven by several factors: availability of natural resources, particularly coal and iron; a stable political system; a growing consumer market; and a culture of innovation. The introduction of the steam engine, mechanical loom, and later the railway system transformed production, transportation, and daily life. However, this period also brought significant social upheaval, including child labor, urban poverty, and environmental degradation." },
  { title: "Interview: Olympic Athlete", category: "Sports", difficulty: "Beginner",
    transcript: "So tell us about your training routine. Well, I train about six hours a day, six days a week. My morning starts at 5 AM with a two-hour swimming session. After breakfast, I do strength training for about an hour. In the afternoon, I have another pool session focusing on technique. Nutrition is incredibly important too. I work with a sports dietitian who plans every meal. The mental aspect is often overlooked. I work with a sports psychologist to handle competition pressure and visualization techniques. It's not just about physical ability; the mental game is what separates good athletes from great ones." },
  { title: "Lecture on Behavioral Economics", category: "Academic", difficulty: "Advanced",
    transcript: "Behavioral economics challenges the traditional economic assumption of rational actors. Daniel Kahneman and Amos Tversky's prospect theory demonstrated that people evaluate gains and losses differently, with losses weighing roughly twice as heavily as equivalent gains. This asymmetry explains phenomena like the endowment effect, where people value objects they own more highly than identical objects they don't. Richard Thaler's concept of mental accounting shows how people treat money differently depending on its source or intended use, even though money is fungible. These insights have profound implications for policy design." },
  { title: "Documentary: Volcanic Islands", category: "Nature", difficulty: "Intermediate",
    transcript: "Volcanic islands represent natural laboratories for studying evolution and ecology. When a new island emerges from the ocean, it is completely barren. Over time, wind and ocean currents bring seeds, insects, and eventually larger animals. This process of ecological succession can take centuries. The Galápagos Islands, perhaps the most famous volcanic archipelago, inspired Darwin's theory of evolution by natural selection. Each island's unique conditions led to the development of distinct species. Today, these islands face threats from invasive species, climate change, and increasing tourism pressures." },
  { title: "Panel Discussion: Future of Work", category: "Business", difficulty: "Intermediate",
    transcript: "Let's discuss what the workplace will look like in 2030. Remote work is clearly here to stay, but I think the real transformation will come from AI automation. McKinsey estimates that up to 30% of current work activities could be automated by 2030. This doesn't necessarily mean job losses but rather job transformation. Workers will need to continuously upskill and reskill. The most valued human skills will be creativity, critical thinking, emotional intelligence, and complex problem-solving. Companies that invest in employee development will have a significant competitive advantage." },
  { title: "Science Talk: Quantum Computing", category: "Technology", difficulty: "Advanced",
    transcript: "Quantum computing represents a fundamental shift in how we process information. Classical computers use bits that are either 0 or 1, while quantum computers use qubits that can exist in superposition, being both 0 and 1 simultaneously. This enables quantum computers to solve certain problems exponentially faster than classical machines. Current applications include cryptography, drug discovery, and optimization problems. However, quantum computers are extremely sensitive to environmental interference, requiring near-absolute-zero temperatures. Google's quantum supremacy demonstration in 2019 showed a calculation that would take a classical supercomputer 10,000 years completed in 200 seconds." },
  { title: "Radio Program: Music and the Brain", category: "Cultural", difficulty: "Intermediate",
    transcript: "Music has a profound and measurable effect on the human brain. Listening to music activates regions associated with emotion, memory, motor skills, and language processing simultaneously. This is why music therapy has proven effective for patients recovering from stroke, managing chronic pain, and even slowing cognitive decline in dementia patients. The 'Mozart effect,' while often overstated in popular culture, does have a kernel of truth: certain types of music can temporarily enhance spatial-temporal reasoning. Playing a musical instrument is particularly beneficial, as it requires coordination of multiple brain functions simultaneously." },
  { title: "Workshop: Public Speaking Skills", category: "Education", difficulty: "Beginner",
    transcript: "Public speaking consistently ranks among people's greatest fears, but it's a skill that can be developed with practice. The foundation of effective public speaking is preparation. Know your material thoroughly, but don't memorize it word for word. Instead, create a clear structure with key points you want to convey. Body language accounts for over half of your impact on an audience. Make eye contact, use natural gestures, and move purposefully. Vocal variety keeps audiences engaged. Vary your pace, volume, and pitch. Practice with a timer to manage your time effectively. Record yourself to identify areas for improvement." },
  { title: "Lecture on Renewable Materials", category: "Science", difficulty: "Intermediate",
    transcript: "The development of renewable and biodegradable materials is essential for a sustainable future. Researchers are creating alternatives to petroleum-based plastics from sources like corn starch, seaweed, and even mushroom mycelium. These bioplastics can decompose in months rather than centuries. Similarly, bamboo and hemp offer sustainable alternatives to wood and cotton, growing much faster and requiring fewer pesticides. The construction industry is exploring cross-laminated timber as a carbon-storing alternative to steel and concrete. However, scaling these innovations requires significant investment in manufacturing infrastructure and consumer education about proper disposal methods." },
  { title: "Discussion: Social Media Impact", category: "Psychology", difficulty: "Intermediate",
    transcript: "The psychological impact of social media is a subject of intense debate. Research shows that heavy social media use correlates with increased rates of anxiety and depression, particularly among adolescents. The mechanism appears to involve social comparison, where users measure their lives against curated highlights of others. Fear of missing out, or FOMO, drives compulsive checking behavior. However, social media also provides genuine benefits: maintaining long-distance relationships, finding community support, and accessing information. The key seems to be mindful usage. Setting time limits, curating feeds to include positive content, and prioritizing in-person interactions can mitigate negative effects." },
  { title: "Seminar on Data Science", category: "Technology", difficulty: "Advanced",
    transcript: "Data science has emerged as one of the most influential fields in modern business and research. The ability to extract meaningful insights from large datasets drives decision-making across industries. Machine learning algorithms identify patterns that humans might miss, from fraud detection in banking to predictive maintenance in manufacturing. However, the field faces challenges including data quality, reproducibility of results, and the shortage of qualified professionals. Ethical considerations around data collection and use are increasingly important. The democratization of data science tools means that basic analytics capabilities are becoming accessible to non-specialists, while advanced applications still require deep expertise." },
  { title: "Tour Guide: Ancient Rome", category: "Cultural", difficulty: "Beginner",
    transcript: "Welcome to the Roman Forum, the heart of ancient Rome for over a thousand years. This was where political speeches were made, trials held, and religious ceremonies performed. To your right, you can see the remains of the Temple of Saturn, one of the oldest temples in Rome, dating back to 497 BCE. The arch ahead is the Arch of Septimius Severus, built in 203 CE to celebrate military victories. Notice how the ancient street level is several meters below the modern city. Centuries of debris and construction have raised Rome's ground level significantly. The Forum provides a fascinating window into daily life in the ancient world." },
];

